            <div type="enclosed">
               <note type="editorial">This may be in Ingleby's hand. The views listed do not
                    feature in the NLW Ingleby Collection, where the items are dated to the 1790s,
                    but are clearly intended for Bull's extra-illustrated A Tour in Wales</note>
                <table>
                    <row role="data">

                        <cell role="data">
                            <rs type="art" ref="ardb.xml#ar0019 ardb.xml#ar0020">2
                                Views of <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0788">Hawarden
                                    Castle</placeName>
                            </rs>
                           <note type="editorial">A watercolour painting signed by Moses Griffith
                                of 'Hawarden Castle' is included in NLW, Pennant's extra-illustrated
                                Tour in Wales, ONE; another, unsigned, watercolour appears in NLW,
                                Pennant's extra-illustrated Tour in Wales, SEVEN, p. 97.</note> at
                                10<hi rend="superscript">£</hi>.. 6<hi rend="superscript">s</hi>
                            each – – –</cell>
                        <cell role="data">1.1.0</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row role="data">

                        <cell role="data">1 <rs type="art" ref="ardb.xml#ar0021">Ditto of <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0792">Wrexham</placeName> Church</rs>
                           <note type="editorial">For a watercolour painting of 'Wrexham Town &amp;
                                Church', see NLW, Pennant, extra-illustrated Tour in Wales, TWO (2nd
                                edn., 1784).</note> – – – – – –</cell>
                        <cell role="data">0.10.6</cell>

                    </row>
                    <row role="data">

                        <cell role="data">1 <rs type="art" ref="ardb.xml#ar0022">Ditto of <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0793">Llangollen</placeName> Bridge</rs>
                           <note type="editorial">A watercolour painting entitled 'Llangollen
                                Bridge and Town' is included in NLW, Pennant, extra-illustrated Tour
                                in Wales, TWO (2nd edn., 1784). The bridge is mentioned in the first
                                edn., A tour in Wales (1778), p. 279.</note> – – – – – – –</cell>
                        <cell role="data">0.10.6</cell>

                    </row>
                    <row role="data">

                        <cell role="data">1 <rs type="art" ref="ardb.xml#ar0023">
                                <choice>
