            </div>
            <div type="letter">
                <opener>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>above is a copy of <persName ref="pe0324">Ingleby</persName>'s Bill
                    which shall be sent with its receit as soon as I can get a frank. I hope you
                    will approve it; but I do not think it unreasonable as he assures me he had two
                    months hard work. copies of any other drawings of mine will be freely at <choice>
                        <abbr>y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                        </abbr>
                        <expan>your</expan>
                    </choice> service. Please to pay the 8 guineas <add place="above">on my
                        account</add> into <persName ref="pe0329">Mess<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Gosling</persName>'s hands; &amp; favor me
                    with their receit at any time. I rejoice at <choice>
                        <abbr>y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                        </abbr>
                        <expan>your</expan>
                    </choice> freedom from <choice>
                        <abbr>y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                        </abbr>
                        <expan>your</expan>
                    </choice>
                    <sic>parlementary</sic> labors.<note type="editorial">Richard Bull left
                        Parliament in 1780. LINK TO FOOTNOTE IN no. 7</note> hard indeed is the
                    service of an honest man in these days when so much is to <sic>reprehended
                    </sic> on each side. The critical situation we are in gives me many an anxious
                    moment.<note type="editorial">Britain was at war with the Americans, whose
                        numbers were boosted in July 1780 by the arrival of a contingent of French
                        soldiers.</note> I heartily wish you a good journey to <placeName ref="pldb.xml#pl0796">Bath</placeName>: on <choice>
                        <abbr>y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                        </abbr>
                        <expan>your</expan>
                    </choice> return I shall make free to trouble you with inspecting the binding of
                    four books as you so kindly offer. Perhaps by that time there may be some news
                    of the remainder of the letter press of the swiss views.<note type="editorial">LINK TO FOOTNOTE in no. 8 on 'swiss views'</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>I am, Dear Sir, <lb/>
                        <choice>
                        <abbr>Y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                            </abbr>
                        <expan>Your</expan>
                    </choice> obliged &amp; faithful <choice>
                        <abbr>H. Serv<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>
                            </abbr>
                        <expan>Humble Servant</expan>
                    </choice>
                    </salute>
                    <signed>
                        <persName ref="pe0232">
                            <choice>
                                <abbr>Tho.</abbr>
                                <expan>Thomas</expan>
                            </choice> Pennant</persName>
                    </signed>
